article.description:
David Robinson moved within 12 points of 20,000 for his career, and Tim Duncan had
                      25 points and 12 rebounds Sunday as the San Antonio Spurs began the easiest stretch of their schedule
                      with a 99-83 victory ov
article.headline: Duncan, Robinson too much for Knicks
article.linkText: Spurs kick off easy stretch by thumping Knicks
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The schedule now includes a parade of patsies for the San Antonio Spurs, who easily dispatched the New York Knicks to begin a stretch of seven games against some of the NBA's worst teams. David Robinson close to 12 points of 20,000 for his career, and Tim Duncan had 25 points and 12 rebounds Sunday as San Antonio defeated New York 99-83. The Spurs won their second consecutive while starting a string of games against the Knicks, Warriors, Rockets, Bulls (twice), Nuggets and Grizzlies. San Antonio does not play a team with a winning record until March 16 against Boston. The Spurs are third in the Midwest Division and fifth in the Western Conference. To have any chance of finishing in the top four in the conference or atop their division, the Spurs believe they will need to go 7-0 over this current stretch. "Absolutely, this is huge for us," Duncan said. "This is the exact kind of stretch we need to really build our confidence and get this team rolling in the right direction. Once we start rolling and guys are feeling good, I think it will snowball and be good for us." Robinson had 13 points and 15 rebounds, and Steve Smith added 18 points, getting the better of his matchup with former Olympic teammate Allan Houston. Kurt Thomas had 19 points and 11 rebounds for the Knicks, who fell behind by 21 points during the third quarter and barely put up a fight the rest of the way. Chairman James Dolan of Cablevision, the corporate owner of the team, marched stern-faced down the hallway toward the locker room after the game. He did not speak to the team, Knicks forward Othella Harrington said. New York fell 15 games below .500 and 16½ games behind the first-place New Jersey Nets in the Atlantic Division. "I can't say I've necessarily conceded that (the Knicks won't make the playoffs), but I'm close to it," Latrell Sprewell said. "It's not like we're making any improvements." The Spurs took control right from the beginning. After the Knicks won the opening tipoff, Smith stripped the ball from Houston and went in for an uncontested layup. San Antonio built its lead after Duncan went to the bench early in the second quarter, increasing a 30-25 advantage to 38-29 before he returned. Robinson, who will become the 27th player in league history to reach 20,000, had a double-double by halftime with 10 points and 10 rebounds as the Spurs led 48-37. "All that stuff just comes because you've been in the league so long," Robinson said. "That's real nice. It's a special club to be in, guys who scored 20,000 points, it means you really stuck in there year in and year out, so I feel really good about that." Smith scored consecutive baskets on isolation plays against Houston, then found Bruce Bowen open in the corner for a 3-pointer that gave San Antonio a 66-48 lead. Tony Parker followed by driving through traffic for a layup and hitting a jumper in transition for a 72-51 lead. The Knicks closed to 13 after Shandon Anderson and Sprewell hit 3-pointers early in the fourth, but Duncan answered with a three-point play, and Antonio Daniels made a layup to get the lead back to 18. Game notes
Smith shot 1-for-1 from 3-point range, increasing his league-leading percentage to .495. ... Howard Eisley retained the backup point guard job for the Knicks, replacing Charlie Ward. Eisley finished with two points and one assist in 18 minutes. ... San Antonio's road record is 18-12, the third-best in the NBA. ... Of San Antonio's 38 victories, 23 have been by 10 points or more. ... The game was a quick one, lasting only 1:54. It was originally scheduled to be shown by NBC, which dropped the telecast after the Knicks fell into last place in the Atlantic Division.
